# TO CREATE A TABLE OF MISSING VALUES A FUNCTION IS CREATED
def table_of_missing_values(df):
    missing_values= df.isnull().sum()
    missing_values_percent = 100*missing_values/len(df)

    missing_values_table =pd.concat([missing_values,missing_values_percent],axis=1)

    missing_values_table_renamed = missing_values_table.rename(columns={0: 'Missing values',1:'% of Missing Values'})

    final_missing_value_table = missing_values_table_renamed[
        missing_values_table_renamed.iloc[:,0] != 0].sort_values('% of Missing Values',ascending=False).round(3)

    print('Out of '+str(df.shape[1]) + ' columns,' +
         str(final_missing_value_table.shape[0]) + ' columns have missing values')

    return final_missing_value_table

# FUNCTION FOR PLOTTING HIST FOR NUMBER OF MISSING VALUES
def number_Nan_graph(df):
        x = df.columns
        y = df.isnull().sum()
        sns.set(context='paper')
        plt.figure(figsize=(15,8)) # change figsize accordingly
        sns.barplot(x,y)
        axis = plt.gca()
        for p in axis.patches:
            height = p.get_height()
            axis.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2.,
                    height + 2,
                    int(height),
                    fontsize=12, ha='center', va='bottom')
        axis.set_xlabel("Data Attributes")
        axis.set_ylabel("Count")
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        plt.show()

#ONLY USEFUL FOR CATEGORICAL DATA
 #to make it work on binary data
def variable_distribution(df,variable):
    if df[variable].dtypes == 'object':
        sns.set( context="paper")
        plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
        sns.countplot(df[variable]).set_title('Distribution')
        axis = plt.gca()
        for p in axis.patches:
            height = p.get_height()
            axis.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2.,
                    height + 2,
                    '{:.2f}%'.format(100*(height/len(df[variable]))),
                    fontsize=10, ha='center', va='bottom')
        sns.set(font_scale=1)
        axis.set_xlabel("Labels for {} ".format(variable))
        axis.set_ylabel("Numbers of Observations")
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        plt.show()
    else:
        print('Not useful to plot')

# label encoding for categorical variables that have lte unique values
 # to improve for NaN values
    
le = LabelEncoder()
no_of_col_le= 0
for feature in data_train:
    if data_train[feature].dtype == 'object':
        if len(list(data_train[feature].unique())) <= 2:
            le.fit(data_train[feature])
            data_train[feature]= le.transform(data_train[feature])
            data_test[feature] = le.transform(data_test[feature])
            no_of_col_le += 1

print('Total {} features were label encoded'.format(no_of_col_le))

# LABEL ENCODING OF CATEGORICAL VARIABLES THAT HAVE UNIQUE VALUE OF LESS THAN EQUAL TO TWO
# Create a label encoder object
le = LabelEncoder()
le_count = 0

le = LabelEncoder()
no_of_col_le= 0
for feature in data_train:
    if data_train[feature].dtype == 'object':
        if len(list(data_train[feature].unique())) <= 2:
            le.fit(data_train[feature])
            data_train[feature]= le.transform(data_train[feature])
            data_test[feature] = le.transform(data_test[feature])
            no_of_col_le += 1

print('Total {} features were label encoded'.format(no_of_col_le))
